sically every app you're building is taking advantage of this incredible image gen model to first figure out what you want your interface to look like. Okay, so we got our first one. Looking nice, a little busy. I think it's a little busy. Let's check out the second one. I like that a little bit better. Let's see the third one. Ooh, I like the card style. I think I'm going to go with the card style. Let's just check out four and five here. Four, okay. Okay, looking nice. And then five. I think this is the winner. Green's my favorite color. Let's go. Let's do this. I'm just going to copy this. I'm going to put it in. I'm going to paste it here. I'm going to do this. I'm going to say, \"I love the fifth one, the one with the green accents and cards. Can we start building the app based on that?\" And I know, I know, there's a click to dictate button. Everyone in every video says, \"Hey, why don't you just dictate?\" I like typing. I'm a typer. I enjoy typing. So, we're going to do this. We have it full access. I just do full access for everything. I fully trust the model. We're going to keep it on medium, have the speed high, and I'm going to hit send, and it is going to get to work here. What we're going to see as it builds this out is some of the amazing functionality that really separates ChatGPT from any of the other apps or tools out there. I can't wait to show you what happens when we get into the testing part when it comes to computer use and different things it does with the built-in browser. Stick around for this. I think you're going to be blown away by what it can do. Also, as it builds, we're going to get into a much more advanced workflow after we go through this. I just want to show you all the kind of bells and whistles of ChatGPT 5.5 with Codex. Then we'll get into super advanced right after. I feel like this is a little bit more fun than reading through blog posts, right? I feel like this is a cooler way to do this. And then also, right after that is the big comparison with this in Claude Code with the final recommendation. So, stick around for that. By the way, if you learned anything at all so far, make sure to leave a like down below. Subscribe, turn notifications. Coming up in the next week, I'll do a live boot camp of Codex inside the Vibe Coding Academy. The link for that is down below. It's the number one AI community on planet Earth, so check that out as well. All right, looks like it finished going. Now, here is some really cool strength of the Codex app with ChatGPT 5.5. The integrations with so many different tools are incredible. So, first of all, built-in browser. So, you pop it open and you can immediately see it works with this built-in browser. And if I even go into full screen mode, you can see a lot more of it. And it basically looks exactly like the image gen we got as we were planning this, which is amazing. But let's look at some of the built-in tools here that there's basically no other app on planet Earth has. We can now start editing this app straight from this live browser in Codex. So, there's many tools we have here. First of all, we have this annotate. So, if I go in here, as you can see as I hover around the app, it selects different elements and I can say for it to change different things. So, if I want to go in here, let's add a favorites button up here. So, as I'm building a new prompt, I can immediately put into favorites. So, I put it there and I can say, \"Let's add a favorites button.\" This is one of my favorite ways to use ChatGPT 5.5 in Codex is instead of just prompting back and forth, I just go straight into the app and I start annotating live on the app. It's like I'm actually building the app inside the app rather than just talking to a chatbot. So, I'm going to say this, I'm going to hit that, I'm going to add it, and then I'm going to hit send on that. And now it's going to get to work. This is one of the most fun ways for me to be building out my apps. And boom, just 