e're going to talk about a multi- aent\napproach. which we'll talk about Hermes\nin a second as well. But one last thing\nI'll leave you off with is my fa one of\nmy favorite things to do with OpenClaw\nis have it build out prototypes on the\ngo. So if I'm on the go, I'm out getting\na Big Mac in McDonald's. I'm out at the\ngym getting a huge pump on, right? I\nwill have my phone on me and whenever I\nget new ideas, the most ideas I come up\nwith either at the gym or when I'm\neating a Big Mac, I'll go on Telegram\nand I'll say, \"Hey, can you build out a\nprototype for this idea for me?\" and\nI'll just spam it with ideas all day\nlong and then when I get back to my\ncomputer, OpenClaw will have built out\nall those prototypes for me and I can\nthen just go and test them very easily.\nSo using OpenClaw as a prototype builder\nwhen you're out on the go, fantastic way\nto use it as well. And real quick before\nwe talk about the multi- aent approach,\nso talking about having multiple agents,\nmultiple open claws, having Hermes set\nup as well. This is a question you get\nall the time. when to use claw code,\nwhen to use openclaw and hermes. Claude\ncode is great for building out consumer\napplications. So big consumerf facing\napplications, very complex, a lot to it.\nYou want to be using claude code because\nclaude code is built specifically for\nvibe coding. I also like to use claude\ncode just for quick tweaks, changing\nbutton colors, things like that, just\ncuz it's easier to go into and get that\nchanged. Openclaw Hermes is great for\nbeing an advisor to building those apps\nout, right? You want to have an agent\nfor building and an agent for advising.\nOpen Claw great for advising mostly\nbecause it knows the most about you. It\nhas huge memory about you and everything\nyou do. So, it's going to be really good\nat advising on those coding projects.\nAnd it's also great at managing files on\nyour computer. So, you're changing\ndifferent things on your computer can\nmanage those files as well. So, from a\ncoding perspective, I use Claude Code as\nthe main driver for building consumer\napps. And then I use OpenClaw as an\nadvisor or as an integration in linear\nas I showed you before where I'll be\nworking with claude code to build things\nand then I'll assign tasks to my open\nclaw in linear to build out other\nfeatures as well. This is the split and\nthere's way more to it as well. I'm just\ngoing over this quick. I mean clawed\ncode you're only using anthropic models\nat the time of this filming. Yes,\nanthropic models are the best when it\ncomes to coding. But if you want to use\nother models, if you want to use local\nmodels, which we'll talk about soon, the\nonly way to do that will be OpenClaw\nbecause it's open- source and\ncustomizable. So that's the split\nbetween these two. So let's talk about\nthe multi- aent approach real quick.\nEveryone and their mothers is talking\nabout Hermes right now on Twitter.\nHermes is another agent just like\nOpenClaw. This is Hermes agent website\nright here. It's fantastic. It's the\nsame exact setup with just the one line\nuh that you paste into your terminal.\nIt's great. I find it to be actually\nslightly more performant and less\nbloated than OpenClaw. It moves a bit\nfaster. It uses less tokens. That's its\nadvantage. As a disadvantage, I found\nthat the memory isn't quite as good in\nOpenClaw. And this is based on my\npersonal experience. Whenever I say\nthis, I get a tremendous amount of\npeople angry at me because for some\nreason there's this weird tribalism in\nAI. But based on my own personal\nexperiences, Hermes Agent's still great.\nIt just the memory doesn't quite match\nOpenClaw. It seems to just forget things\na lot for me, but it is more performant.\nSo, I will say this, I don't think you\ncan go wrong with either. I think\nthey're a lot closer in performance than\nmost people on the internet are making\nout to me. For some reason on the\ninternet, most people are like, \"Oh, no\nHermes is the absolute best. Never use\nOpenClaw.\" Or, \"Oop Claw is the best.\nNever use Hermes.\" I think that's mostly\njust tribalism. I I feel like people use\neach of these agents as like a a\nbasketball team for some reason where\nit's like, \"No, my basketball team's the\nbest. Your basketball team stinks.\" I\ndon't know why. You'll be a lot more\nproductive if you don't have this kind\nof tribalism mentality where one thing\nhas to be the best and one thing has to\nbe the worst. I think they're both\ngreat. I think they both have their own\nadvantages and disadvantages. I think\nusing them together is the best possible\nway to be using them because then you\nget the best of both worlds and you see\nwhich one fits into your workflows. One\nmight be better for your own personal\nworkflows than the other and that's\ntotally fine. I'm not paid by OpenClaw.\nI'm not paid by Hermes. I'm not paid by\nany of these companies cuz I don't\nreally take sponsorships from anyone cuz\nI want to give you unbiased opinions. So\nhere would be my recommendation. Use\nthem both. Use them side by side. How do\nyou use them side by side is the\nquestion. Well, let me show you inside\nof Telegram. I have two things going on\nhere. I have my Henry group chat, which\nyou see as this blue square right there,\nand then I have my Hermes regular chat\nand I can speak to Hermes right through\nhere. I have them working side by side\non this computer. You can put them on\nseparate computers if you want. The only\nreal advantage to that is they'll have\nseparate workspaces, but if you have a\ngood enough computer, it doesn't really\nmatter. But I use them side by side. If\nOpen Claw is working on one thing, I'll\nhave Hermes go and work on something\nelse completely different. You don't\nneed to give them kind of separate\nroles. Some people say, \"Oh, Hermes is\ntheir coder. Open Claw is their\nresearcher or whatever.\" You don't need\nto do that. They're both more than\ncapable of doing whatever you want. I\nkind of use OpenClaw as more of an\norchestrator where if I'm doing\nsomething really complex, I'll say,\n\"Hey, talk to Hermes and have them do\nthis thing as well.\" That's totally\nfine. But the biggest advantage to\nhaving a multi- aent approach and why I\nthink you should do this and why I think\nyou should set up one open claw and one\nHermes is just for insurance. These apps\nbreak quite a bit and most of all they\nbreak when you update them quite a bit\nas well. The best way to fix them is by\nhaving a second AI agent there as\ninsurance that can go and then fix the\nother agent for you. they can go and see\nwhat you did wrong, see what the update\nbroke and fix it for you and update the\nconfig and all that. This has kept my\nuptime up a lot higher than it was\nbefore. Right before when things would\nbreak, it'd take me a couple hours to\nfix it cuz I didn't have an AI there to\nhelp me out. But when you have two AI\nagents going, a Hermes and an OpenClaw,\nwhen one breaks, you can have the other\ngo and fix it. And it's not like it's\nmore expensive. These are completely\nfree tools. You're just paying for the\ntokens, right? And so if you just plug\nthis in, even if you just plug Hermes\ninto like your Chat GPT subscription or\neven a local model, which I'll talk to\nyou about in the next chapter of this\nvideo, you're not spending much more in\norder to have a lot more insurance, in\norder to get a lot more productivity. So\nthe number one reason to set up two\nagents is so that they're insurance for\neach other to make sure they don't go\ndown. The number two reason is to see\nwhich agent fits better in your\nworkflow. Open Claw or Hermes. I truly\ndon't have a horse in the race. I use\nthem both. I think they're both great. I\ndon't think one's like way worse or\nbetter than the other. So, I just use\nthem side by side. Get them both set up,\nthough, and you'll make sure that your\nagents are always up. You can say, \"Hey,\nOpen Claw just went down. Please fix it,\nHermes.\" Or vice versa, and they'll keep\nthem up and going. So, let's talk about\ncost savings. The best way for cost\nsavings, this is not only about cost\nsavings. This will just get you better\nperformance overall, is the brain and\nmuscle approach. What's the brain and\nmuscle approach? The brain is when you\nhave an orchestrator, right? That you're\nthat's the model you're interfacing\nwith. That's the model that's\ndetermining the task to work on. And\nthen that brain gives tasks it\ndetermines to do to each of the muscles\nit uses. Right? So this could be, you\nknow, a coding muscle, a research\nmuscle, a scraping muscle, things like\nthat. Choosing the appropriate model for\neach one of the brains and muscles is\nhow you a get the most performance and b\ndo the most cost savings, right? Because\nif you just use opus for everything,\nyou're going to spend a tremendous\namount of money. So you want to have the\nright model doing each muscle. So let's\ntalk about what's the best for each. We\ntalked about it earlier. When it comes\nto the brain, the orchestrator, nothing\ncomes close to opus at the moment at the\nrecording of this video. Hopefully in\nthe next week, Chad GBT 5.5 comes out.\nAnd I would be very happy if it's the\nbest model out there for OpenClaw. I'd\nbe very happy. I'm rooting for it. But\nat the moment, we have to face facts. We\nhave to face reality. Opus is the best.\nBut then you have different muscles and\nwe talked about this earlier. I'm not\ngoing to reiterate every single thing\nhere. But Chad GBT for the coding muscle\nis the best. Writing and research any\nsort of cheap model like Gemini will be\ngood here. Gemini flash three flash is\nreally good. But let's talk about local\nmodels here because local models make\nfantastic muscles as well. What is a\nlocal AI model? A local AI model is an\nAI model that runs purely on your\ndevice. At the moment, when you use AI,\nwhen you talk to Opus or Chad GBT, it's\nsending your prompts to the cloud. It's\nsending your prompts to servers in the\nmiddle of a big farm or a suit in space\nthat processes your prompt, figures out\nthe answer, and sends it back to you.\nThis means you require an internet\nconnection. This means all your chats go\nto servers and AI labs that they can\nread it and train their models on. That\nmeans you're paying for every single one\nof these prompts when you do local\nmodels that run on your computers. You\ndon't need the internet. It's completely\nfree, just the cost of your power,\nwhatever it is plugged into the wall.\nAnd it's completely secure. Nothing goes\nto the cloud. Nothing goes to servers\nwhere AI employees can go and read it.\nThis brings a lot of advantages too, as\nin you're not, again, you're not paying\nfor these calls. So, if you use a local\nmodel as like your research muscle,\nwhich is what I do right now, I'm using\nQuen 36 as well as GLM 5.1 as my\nresearch model where it's going on the\ninternet and researching content and\nthings for me all day. Literally every\n20 minutes, one of my local models goes\non the internet and scrapes a website\nlooking for content and opportunities.\nThis again is completely free. It runs\ncompletely locally and it unlocks new\nuse cases because I can run it 247 365.\nIf you ran Opus 247 365, you'd be paying\na million dollars a month. But because I\nuse local models, I can have it running\nevery 20 minutes going online scraping,\nscraping, scraping. So tying in local\nmodels here as your muscles gives you\nreally, really big advantages. Now, what\nhardware do you need for local models?\nThere's good news and bad news. Good\nnews is you can use basically any device\non planet Earth right now and run a\nlocal model on it. Now, if you have a\nbase model Mac Mini that's not that\npowerful, you're not going to run the\nmost powerful local models on planet\nEarth. You could run like a Gemma 4, a\nsmall Gemma 4 that can handle your\nembedding, which is basically your\nmemory management. And there's\nadvantages to that. If you have a Mac\nStudio, a super powerful one, you can\nrun bigger models like GLM 5.1, which is\nprobably the best local model on planet\nEarth right now, that can do big things\nfor you. It can code, it can research,\nit can do a lot of different things. So\ndepending on the hardware you have, you\ncan run a local model, but you should\nstill be paying attention to it. No\nmatter what device you have, you should\nfigure out which local models run on it\nand then find the best use cases for\nthose local models. Best way to figure\nout which local model you should be\nusing, go to your OpenClaw, say, \"Hey,\nhere's the device I have. Here's the\nmemory. Which local models can I run?\"\nAnd of those local models, what are the\nbest workflows and use cases for them\nbased on what you know about me? You do\nthat, you'll get a personalized custom\nrecommendation for which local models\nyou can use for which use cases and\nwhich muscles. You'll save a ton of\nmoney and you'll be learning about\ncuttingedge AI stuff like local models,\nwhich is amazing. If you're running a\nlocal model, you're ahead of 99% of\npeople, which is incredible. By the way,\nif you learned anything so far, I run\nlive openclaw boot camps every single\nFriday in the vibe coding academy. It's\nthe number one AI community on planet\nearth. Over 1,500 people in there\nlearning about open call all day, ask me\nquestions, talking to me live all day.\nLink down below. I promise it'll be the\nbest decision you ever make. Check that\nout down below. Also, subscribe and turn\non notifications if you haven't already.\nAll I do is make amazing videos about\nAI. You learned anything so far? Leave a\nlike. It's the most free way to support\nthe channel. I appreciate you. So, let's\ntalk next about mission control. Mission\ncontrol is probably one of the most\nimportant concepts when it comes to\nOpenClaw. This is a concept I invented a\nfew months ago that now everyone's\ntalking about. And this is basically\nyour own custom software building\nplatform. Any tools you need for your\nOpenClaw, you can build out in your\nmission control. I have a lot going on\nhere. I have a cananband board that has\nall our different tasks in it between me\nand my open cloth. I have an agent\noverview section where I can see all my\nagents working and seeing what they're\ndoing. I have an office view so I can\nliterally watch my agents work in real\ntime as these cool 2D pixelated\ncharacters. I even have a factory where\nI can watch them vibe code for me in\nreal time, which is amazing. Here's the\npoint though. Mission Control is your\nplace to build out any custom software\nyou need to improve your OpenClaw\nexperience. These should all be custom\ntools built for your own workflows.\nWhether it's organization and project\nmanagement, whether it's just fun things\nlike this where you get to watch your\nopen claws work, whether it's a custom\nmemory solution, these are all custom to\nyou. The number one question I get when\nI talk about mission control is, \"Oh,\nopen source your mission control. Open\nsource and give it to us.\" That's really\nI'm going to be honest and this is no\noffense to anyone here. I think that's a\nreally stupid question because this is\nall custom to me. This is all custom to\nmy workflows. This is like me showing\nyou like a really cool pair of Jordan\nones I just bought in my size and you\ngo, \"Oh, give me those. Those are mine.\nGive them to me.\" Well, they're in my\nsize. They have my feet stank in them.\nThey're built just for me. I don't know\nwhy you want them. You can go out and\nget your own in your own size. Do\nwhatever you want in the own colors you\nlike. I don't know why you'd want mine.\nYou should be building your own mission\ncontrol for your own use cases that are\ncustom to you. And you need to be doing\nthis. Even if you've never coded before,\nyou need to be building a mission\ncontrol. Cuz here's how I think about\nit. Whenever I'm doing something with\nHenry, my open claw, and it doesn't have\nthe tools it needs to do that task, I\njust go, \"Hey, build that out in our\nmission control. Add that as a new\ntool.\" And he'll build it out and he'll\nbe able to use it moving forward. Like\nwhen it wasn't remembering things for\nme, I had to build out its own memory\nsystem and put it in the mission\ncontrol. When it was creating docs for\nme and it was just being placed in\nrandom places on my computer and I\ncouldn't find them. I said, \"Hey, make a\ndoc section so I can read all those\ndocs.\" And anytime you need a tool, you\njust go to your open claw and you say,\n\"Hey, build a tool out for me. Put it in\nour mission control and start using it\nmoving forward.\" I'm thinking about open\nsourcing mine. If I do it, I'm going to\nput in the vibe coding academy. I think\nit's better for people that I don't do\nit to be quite honest only because you\nreally should be making this custom for\nyour own use cases. Copying other people\nwhether it's use cases or mission\ncontrols, it doesn't do you any good.\nFirst of all, half the fun is building\nthese things out by yourself. The other\nhalf is these need to be custom for what\nyou're doing. So mission control, build\nit out. Great reverse prompting\nopportunity. Hey, OpenClaw, based on\nwhat you know about me, what tools can\nwe add to our mission control? It'll\ngive you a list of them to say, hey,\nbuild them out and you'll be good to go.\nSo, let's talk about security. This is a\nbig one. This is one I get most\nquestions on is security. And for good\nreasons, right? You have an AI agent\nliving on your computer that can do\nanything, that has access to all your\nnudes and your photos and everything\nelse you do. You need to have good\nsecurity. But here's the thing, though.\nThere is no good blanket security\nrecommendation I can give to you, right?\nIt's an AI employee that can do anything\non your computer. If I sat here and gave\nyou every security recommendation, we'd\nbe here for 15 hours plus. So, here's\nwhat you need to do. If you can master\nthis, you'll be good on security. You\nneed to use good judgment. What do I\nmean by that? Your open claw isn't going\nto do things that you don't tell it to\ndo. What I mean by that is you're not\ngoing to say, \"Hey, write me a\nPowerPoint presentation on local\nmodels.\" And then it goes and leaks all\nyour iMes Twitter. It's not going to do\nthat. That's not how it works. It only\ndoes exactly what you tell it to do. So\nthat means you need to have some\npersonal accountability and you need to\nuse good judgment. You can't say, \"Go\nand check out all my emails,\" and then\ndelete any emails you think are spam.\nBecause if you do that, you're opening\nyourself up for OpenClaw to do things\nthat you don't want it to do. You need\nto use good judgment. You need to use\nprecise languaging on what you ask it to\ndo. And you need to think about the\nrepercussions of it doing what you ask\nit to do. My question to you is this\nbecause security makes a lot of people\nreally nervous when it comes to\nOpenClaw. How many people do you know\nhas had catastrophic security events\nbecause of OpenClaw? My guess would be\nfor 99.99999%\nof you, you don't know a single person\nwho's had a catastrophic security event.\nThat doesn't mean there aren't\nvulnerabilities. That just means there's\na lot of panic over nothing here. If you\njust use good judgment, think about\nwhat's going to happen with every prompt\nyou give it. I'm very confident bad\nthings won't happen to you. So, just\nhave some personal accountability, use\ngood judgment with your prompts, think\nabout what could happen, and you'll be\ngood to go. Again, you don't say, \"Hey,\nwrite me a tweet.\" And then it goes and\nit downloads 20 viruses onto your\ncomputer. That's not how this works.\nOpen Claw does what you say. So, if you\nwant to have good security, think about\nwhat you're asking it to do and make\nsure you're only asking it to do pretty\nsafe things. Those are all my lessons\nlearned after 300 plus hours of using\nOpenClaw. The game is constantly\nchanging. AI models are constantly\nchanging. OpenClaw is constantly\nchanging. These will update as we go all\nthe time. I mean, tomorrow a new model\ncan drop that will change everything I\njust said. So, make sure you're\nsubscribed to notifications on. So, as\nthings change, as things go, you get the\nupdate straight from me. Leave a like if\nyou learned anything at all. Make sure\nto check out the Vibe Coding Academy\nnumber one community AI link for that\ndown below. Hope you learned something.\nI'm so so grateful if you made it past\nthis entire video that you would sit\nhere listen to me all day. I still can't\nbelieve how much this channel's blown up\nover the last few months. I am so so so\nso grateful for you watching and\nlistening and enjoying the content.\n\n3.2s · 46m 48s YouTube · 9.7k words · text via transcript/captionTracks","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-rex"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777347654905}}
{"type":"message","id":"41c6dd81","parentId":"0152b678","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:41:45.197Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Got the transcript for video 3. Let me save it now.","thinkingSignature":"b3c9e46b21410b874da21ad74828a5f620580dd3b9ad03312c85e8eaf136ec7a"},{"type":"text","text":"Got it. Saving video 3 now.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_bliybjoqf4r1_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - OpenClaw Full Tutorial - Alex Finn.md","content":"# OpenClaw Full Tutorial: Set Up Your First AI Employee!\n\n**Channel:** Alex Finn  \n**Date:** 2026-04-27  \n**Original Video:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGcdxFPwBdU  \n**Duration:** 46 minutes 48 seconds  \n**Views:** 52K  \n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nAlex Finn's comprehensive OpenClaw tutorial based on 3+ months of heavy usage. Covers what OpenClaw is, device hosting, model selection, communication channels, use cases, multi-agent setup (OpenClaw + Hermes), cost optimization, mission control, and security.\n\n### What Is OpenClaw\n- Completely autonomous AI agent that works 24/7\n- Lives where YOU work (Telegram, Discord, etc.)\n- Self-improving — builds skills over time\n- Can manage devices, build apps, change settings, post content, scrape web, research\n- **Fully open source** — your data stays on your device, use any model (Claude, GPT, local), customize everything\n- Private and secure\n\n### Where to Host\n- **Any device** — even an old laptop from 15 years ago works\n- **NOT a VPS** — significantly worse experience, less secure, less usable. Alex will never take VPS sponsorships.\n- Mac Mini is popular because it's a great value, easy to remote into, fun to have on your desk\n- Can also run on your main daily driver computer\n- **Scale slowly**: start with what you have → then Mac Mini → then Mac Studio for local models\n- No need to spend thousands upfront\n\n### Model Recommendations\n\n| Role | Model | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Orchestrator (brain)** | Opus 4.7 (via API) | Best task completion reliability. Claude will \"crawl to the finish line with a katana cut off its leg.\" ChatGPT will \"roll over and give up\" when it stubs a toe. |\n| **Coding muscle** | ChatGPT 5.4 | Incredible at coding, high limits, cheap |\n| **Research/writing** | Gemini Flash 3 (free via Google account) or ChatGPT | Cheap, plenty good |\n\n- Anthropic banned OpenClaw from subsidized subscriptions, but API still works (optimize to keep costs near $200/mo)\n- **Brains & Muscles approach**: Use Opus as the orchestrator, cheap models for execution tasks = best performance + cost savings\n\n### Local Models (Running on Your Hardware)\n- Run completely offline, free, private\n- Great as \"muscles\" (especially research/scraping)\n- Can run 24/7 without massive costs (e.g., have a local model scrape websites every 20 minutes)\n- **Best local models**: GLM 5.1 (best overall), Qwen 3.6\n- Ask OpenClaw: \"What local models can I run on my device?\" then \"Which use cases fit those models?\"\n\n### Communication Channels\n\n**Telegram (best for main chat):**\n- Free, easy bot setup\n- Group chats with Topics = separate context for different projects (saves tokens + stays organized)\n- Setup: Create group → add bot → create topics → bot responds per topic\n- If topics don't work, ask your agent to fix it\n- Stores memories and agent rules with every chat\n\n**Discord (for automated workflows):**\n- Great for automated workflows (dropping content, scripts, alerts)\n- Weaknesses: doesn't send all memories/rules with every chat\n- Use for automated content dropping, not main chatting\n\n### Finding Your OWN Use Cases (Key Exercise)\n1. **Brain dump everything about yourself** into OpenClaw (your business, goals, metrics, habits)\n2. **For one day**: carry a notepad and write down every manual task you do on your computer\n3. **At end of day**: dump that task list into OpenClaw\n4. **Then ask**: \"Based on everything you know about me, my goals, and what I do manually, what workflows and use cases can we implement?\"\n5. OpenClaw generates personalized use cases — choose 1-2 and implement\n\n### Example Use Cases Alex Uses\n\n1. **Linear Integration (Vibe Coding):** OpenClaw fully integrated with Linear (project management). Assigns tasks to agents → agent pulls code from GitHub → completes task → creates PR. Massive vibe coding multiplier.\n\n2. **Content Scouting (Discord automated):** Agent monitors Twitter/YouTube for Claude Code and OpenClaw trends. When content starts trending → alerts in Discord + drafts scripts based on trending topics. Stays on top of viral opportunities.\n\n3. **AI Stock Research:** Agent looks for AI investing opportunities, bottlenecks in AI supply chain, surfaces daily stock research reports. (Alex is a big AI investor.)\n\n4. **On-the-Go Prototype Builder:** When out at gym or getting food, sends ideas via Telegram → OpenClaw builds prototypes while away → ready to test when back at computer.\n\n### Multi-Agent Approach: OpenClaw + Hermes\n\n**Hermes Agent** = similar to OpenClaw, slightly more performant, uses fewer tokens, slightly less memory quality.\n\n**Why use both:**\n1. **Insurance**: When one breaks (especially after updates), the other can fix it → keeps uptime near 100%\n2. **Side-by-side productivity**: Have both working on different tasks simultaneously\n3. **Best of both worlds**: Use whichever fits your workflow better for each task\n\n**Don't think of it as tribal warfare**: Both are great. OpenClaw's memory is slightly better. Hermes is slightly faster. Use both.\n\n### Mission Control (Custom Software Platform)\n- Your custom-built tool suite for OpenClaw\n- Alex's includes: Kanban board, agent overview dashboard, office view (watch 2D pixel agents work in real time), factory (watch vibe coding happen live)\n- **Key principle**: Build tools for YOUR workflows, not copy others\n- Workflow: \"Whenever OpenClaw needs a tool it doesn't have → say 'Hey, build that in our mission control' and it will\"\n- **Reverse prompt**: \"Based on what you know about me, what tools should we add to our mission control?\"\n\n### OpenClaw vs Claude Code\n- **Claude Code**: Best for building consumer-facing applications, quick tweaks (button colors, etc.), uses Anthropic models only\n- **OpenClaw**: Great for advising, managing files, Linear integration, any model (including local), runs 24/7\n- **Best setup**: Claude Code as main builder + OpenClaw as advisor/integrator working in parallel via Linear\n\n### Security\n- No blanket security recommendation fits everyone\n- OpenClaw only does exactly what you tell it to do\n- Use good judgment: think about what you're asking and potential repercussions\n- 99.99% of users experience zero catastrophic security events\n- Personal accountability matters\n\n---\n\n## Full Transcript\n\n[Full transcript is approximately 9,700 words. See source video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGcdxFPwBdU]\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":49908,"output":1568,"cacheRead":27269,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":78745,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777347654908,"responseId":"063f5f47d75f40f5440d04c3d5b19cee"}}
{"type":"message","id":"31e2fb78","parentId":"41c6dd81","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:41:45.226Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_bliybjoqf4r1_1","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 6337 bytes to /Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - OpenClaw Full Tutorial - Alex Finn.md"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777347705225}}
{"type":"message","id":"7f9ea6fa","parentId":"31e2fb78","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:41:52.038Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Video 3 is done. Now moving on to video 4: \"7 Claude Code secrets you had NO idea about\" - 13 min 3 sec, URL `watch?v=8YhYtIF9PYI`. Let me transcribe it. But first, I need to check - is this the stopping point video `Qkqe-uRhQJE`? No, that's not this one. Let me continue.","thinkingSignature":"79a130ff1bd8e057cf226885031753263242347f7e9915d5092063dbfb7ebadb"},{"type":"text","text":"✅ **Video 3 complete.**\n\n**Video 4:** \"7 Claude Code secrets you had NO idea about\" — 13 min\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_k1d660wru9oy_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"summarize \"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8YhYtIF9PYI\" --youtube auto --extract-only","timeout":120}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":51540,"output":176,"cacheRead":27269,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":78985,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777347705232,"responseId":"063f5f793b7fd289edb052d13f1ce8ed"}}
{"type":"message","id":"8a648b07","parentId":"7f9ea6fa","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:41:55.790Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_k1d660wru9oy_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nThe creator of Claude Code just revealed\nseven secrets to get the most out of\nClaude Code and Opus 47. In this video,\nwe'll not only go over every single\nsecret he revealed, but also demonstrate\nthem live as we build an app together.\nBy the end of this video, if you follow\nalong, you'll not only be a master of\nClaude code and Opus 47, but you'll also\nhave an entire amazing app that you'll\nbuild out side by side with me, even if\nyou've never coded before a day in your\nlife. Let's lock in and get into it. So,\nBoris Churnney, one of the creators of\nClaude Code, just put out two things.\nThis amazing thread on X that goes over\nall these tips and tricks, as well as an\nentire blog post with a bunch of tips\nand tricks. What we're going to do is\nnot spend the next 20 minutes reading\nthe blog post and thread word by word\nlike every other AI channel out there.\nWe're instead going to be about that\naction boss. We're going to go in and\nimplement every single one of these into\na live app we're going to build\ntogether. So, let's do this. We're going\nto do this all in the Claude Code CLI. I\nknow in the last video I said Claude\nDesktop is the best way to use Claude\nCode at the moment. The thing is a lot\nof these new features they just dropped\non our heads for some reason's only\navailable in the CLI. So, we're going to\ndo this in the CLI for now. The first\ntrick before we start building this app\nis we're going to go into auto mode. So,\nif you hit shift tab, then shift tab,\nthen shift tab, you will see auto mode.\nAnd yes, we're going to make it the\ndefault mode. Auto mode is really cool\nbecause it's going to make claude code\ngo so much faster. My one complaint\nabout claude code to be honest with you\nis it just asks for permission way too\nmuch. If you're trying to build complex\napps like I am, every literal 5 seconds\nit's asking, \"Hey, can I do this? Hey,\ncan I do that? Hey, can I do this?\" Even\nwhen you're in accepted edit mode, it's\ndoing that. The issue is is now\neverything requires your attention every\n5 seconds. You can't multitask and do\nother things. Well, they just released\nthis fix. They released auto mode, which\nis now what I recommend as a default\nmode for everyone using Claude Code.\nWhat it's going to do is it's going to\nuse the AI to determine what permissions\nit should have. So, instead of asking\nyou, should you do this, should it do\nthat, should I have permission for this,\nit's just going to ask itself and kind\nof make good judgment. What this will\nallow it to do is work continuously for\nhours on end without having to interrupt\nyou every five seconds. And that's\nincredible. makes claude code so much\nbetter. So, what I'd highly recommend\ndoing is hitting shift tap until you go\non auto mode. And now, Anthropic will\nhandle all the permissioning itself,\nallowing you to give a prompt, and it\njust goes on its own. That's the first\nof the seven tricks Boris gave. Let's go\ninto the second one here, and let's\nstart building our app out together now\nthat we're in auto mode. The second\ntrick he gave is to frontload as much\ninformation as humanly possible into\ncloud code before you start a session.\nSo, what makes Opus 47 so special is\nit's a lot better at listening to your\ndirections. And so, what you can do is\nwhen you first go into Opus, now that it\ncan run for a long time on its own, you\nwant to frontload as many instructions\nas humanly possible because it will be\nreally good at parsing and following all\nthose instructions without having to\ninterrupt you at all. So, let's build\nthis app out together. I'll put this\nprompt down below. What we're going to\ndo is build a really helpful app. If\nyou're at all familiar with Linear, it's\nthe number one project management tool\nright now. It's like completely free and\nawesome. But I personally like building\nmy own version of every app I use. So,\nwe're going to build our own version of\nLinear. And if you do this with me,\nyou'll have an awesome app that you can\nuse for the rest of your life. It's\nreally good at helping you manage your\ntasks and projects. So, before when I\nwas building out projects in Cloud Code\nor Codeex, I would kind of build it out\none step at a time. Just give the first\nstep and the second step and the third\nstep and the fourth step. What we're\ngoing to do instead is we're just going\nto give it all at once. I want to build\na linear clone out. This should be a\nproject management tool where I can\nbuild projects, then put tasks and\nissues in those projects. Every project\ntask and issue should have status and\npriority. It should be a really clean,\nsimplistic, linear-like interface. I\nshould be able to assign users to each\ntask and add any other features you\nthink will be helpful. Use NextJS to\nbuild this out. Next.js, just a web\nframework a lot of popular web apps are\nbuilt on. We'll make this really easy to\nbuild. And I'm going to hit enter on\nthat. What you're going to see now is\nClaude Code will be able to obey every\nsingle instruction I gave that I\nfrontloaded there. And I'm not going to\nhave to give permission all. It's just\ngoing to do it all at once because we're\nin auto mode. And in a second, I'm going\nto give you two more tricks that are\ngoing to be really amazing and make this\nexperience so much better. But let's get\nthe V1 of this app done. And if you took\nthe prompt down below and used it,\nyou're going to have a really amazing\napp with me here. And just as this is\nbuilding, I get this question all the\ntime. Hey, when should I be using Claude\ncode? When should I be using OpenClaw to\nbuild things? Just as a reminder, as\nthis is building out, I like to use\nOpenClaw to build prototypes of apps\nwhen I'm on the go since I can just hit\nit up in Telegram. I also like to use\nOpenClaw for building out tooling for\nOpenClaw. So, building out tools for my\nagent to use. But when I'm building out\ndeep complex apps, if I'm building out\nconsumerf facing apps, if I'm going into\na deep coding session like we're doing\nright here, I'm using claw code, it's\njust going to be a lot better at coding\nby itself. All right, looks like it's\ndone and it's already running. Let's\ntake a look to see what we got here. And\nboom, look at that. That's good looking.\nAnyone who's ever used linear before\nwill definitely recognize this. So, what\nyou can see here is a list of the tasks\nthat are assigned to each project. So,\nwe can go in, we can create new tasks.\nLet's say finish this YouTube video. Put\nit in to-do. Assign it to me. Create.\nAnd boom. This is beautiful. I mean,\nthis looks pretty much exactly like\nlinear. Uh, this is really, really nice.\nYou even have tags in it. This is great.\nIf you took the prompt from down below,\nyou now have an awesome project\nmanagement tool you can be doing for all\nyour vibe coding. This is sick. Which\nbrings us to the third tip that they\nrevealed in the thread and blog post\nthat they just released, which is recap.\nIf you do slashrecap,\nthis will generate a oneline sentence\nrecap of everything your agent has done\nto this point. This is really helpful\nbecause if you followed my previous tips\naround front-loading information and\nhaving your agent run for hours on end,\nit'll do a whole bunch of things that\nyou're not even aware about. If you use\nslashrecap after a long running session\nor after maybe you've gone to bed and\nyou woke up the next morning and want to\nget back to work, it will give you a\nrundown of everything you've done up to\nthat point. This is unbelievably helpful\nif you treat claude code like an\nemployee, which you should be doing, and\nletting it just do its thing for long\nperiods of time. Which brings us to our\nnext tip, which is effort level. They\nmade it a lot more configurable how much\neffort your model puts in when you give\nit tasks to do. So, if you do\nslasheffort, you hit enter there, you\ncan select your effort level. So,\nthey've added a couple things here.\nFirst, they added extra high and max\nmode. And what I found based on my tests\nis you basically want extra high for\npretty much everything unless you give a\nsuper complex task. So, what I would\nrecommend is if you do what I said\nearlier, which is give, you know,\nfront-loaded information on every single\nthing you want in app, I would go into\nmax mode for that. And then afterwards,\nas you're configuring, adding new\nfeatures, changing things around, switch\nit to extra high mode. The only reason I\nwould ever use high, medium, low, is if\none, you're not on the $200 a month\nplan, which I highly recommend. If\nyou're on the lower plans, then I\nprobably would want to get more granular\nand switch to low for things like\nchanging button colors and things like\nthat. But other than that, if you're on\nthe $200 a month plan, I've gotten away\nwith using extra high for pretty much\neverything other than that front-loaded\nmax big prompt I give to kick off apps.\nSo, if I'm you, use extra high for\npretty much everything, unless you're on\none of the lower plans, then you can\nswitch that. But slasheffort will help\nyou configure how much effort it's\nputting in on every single task. The\nnext tip they gave, and they gave this\nin this blog post, I'll put the link for\nthe blog post in the thread down below.\nI think this we're at tip number five\nhere is notifications. You should be\nturning on notifications for cloud code\nso that after it's done running these\nlong running tasks, it'll ping you put a\nnotification in here says, \"Hey, I'm\ndone. Check this out.\" The theme of a\nlot of these tips I'm giving is you're\nnow increasing your trust of clawed code\nto have it run by itself. Instead of\nhandholding it through a whole bunch of\ntasks, you're giving it trust and you're\nletting it run on its own. So what you\ncan do to set up notifications is\nactually really simple. Say, hey, set up\nnotifications. So you can say after\nevery piece of work you do, please send\nme a notification. And just by doing\nthat, it's going to set up its own\nautomation to ping you every single time\nit's done something. So I'm going to hit\nenter on that, and it's going to set up\nthat notification. So after long running\ntasks, it pings me, and I can come back\nand quickly get into focus with Claude\nCode. So, as you can see, it's actually\nloading up a skill that can actually\nsend you those notifications. So, it's\nsetting up a skill. It's setting up a\nhook. And every time a prompt is done,\nit's going to use that hook to say,\n\"Hey, Claude Code here, all finished.\nCheck out what we've done.\" This will\nspeed up your workflow so much because\nyou can give a long running task, let it\nwork for a while, come back, and now it\nwill ping you every time it's done. So,\nyou can always stay in flow. By the way,\njust as a little side tip here, what I'm\ndoing when I give these long running\ntasks, I'm always switching to the chat\nin the desktop app. I actually find for\nthe first time, I love just straight up\nchatting with Opus. Previously, I\npreferred chat GBT for chatting and\nbouncing business ideas, but Opus 47 has\nactually been really, really good for me\nwhen it comes to coming up with new\nideas for my business. So, when I give a\nlongunning task to Claude Code and I'm\nwaiting for that notification to come\nin, I'm going to chat mode in the\ndesktop app and I'm talking about\nwhatever it is I'm building and coming\nup with brand new ideas for that app and\nfor that business. Highly recommend that\nworkflow. By the way, before I give this\nlast tip, by the way, leave a like down\nbelow if you learned anything at all.\nMake sure to subscribe and turn on\nnotifications. Also, I do a live boot\ncamp every single Friday in the Vibe\nCoding Academy. I also do live vibe\ncoding sessions every Thursday. So, if\nyou join now, you can hop in, watch me\nvibe code live with Claude Code. I\nnarrate everything I do, show you every\nsingle tip and trick I'm using as I'm\nvibe coding. So, if you want to watch me\nvibe code live and ask me questions as I\ndo it, join the vibe coding academy link\ndown below for that biggest community in\nAI. The last tip I'll give here is\nworking with adaptive thinking. So they\nactually removed extended thinking with\nOpus 47. Before in Opus 46, you can turn\non extended thinking and it will use a\nlot more tokens to think every step of\nthe way. Now instead, what they're\nhaving you do is you're actually going\nto use prompts to initiate extended\nthinking. So for instance, say I want to\nmake it so I can invite other people to\nuse my project management tool, right? I\nwant to invite other people in and they\ncan add task and manage tasks with me.\nThis is great if you have a team. I\nwould say I want to make a collaborative\nmode here where I can invite other\npeople to use this project management\ntool with me. Think carefully step by\nstep about this. So you have two\ndifferent knobs you can control here.\nHow much effort it's putting in and how\nmuch thinking it's going to do. Effort\nis basically going to be in total how\nlong they'll spend on a task you give\nit. And thinking will be how long it\nspends on each individual micro step of\nthat task. I like to use the extended\nthinking for when I give a smaller task\nthat might be more complex like this.\nThis is a collaborative mode. So this\nisn't some gargantuan task that with a\nhundreds of different features in it.\nInstead, it's one task but it's really\nchallenging. So, I want to think extra\nhard about this one simple task. So,\nI'll just say, \"Think carefully step by\nstep.\" If this was a smaller task, like,\n\"Hey, just update the color of a\nbutton.\" I'd go in and I'd say something\nlike, \"Prioritize responding quickly\nrather than thinking deeply.\" So, now\nyou can control the thinking budget of\neach one of these tasks. This is the new\nway to do adaptive thinking. So, just\nputting on some extra prompt that says,\n\"Think hard about this or don't think\ntoo much about this at all.\" This will\ncontrol the amount of tokens that are\nspent on each individual task rather\nthan overall. Those were the seven tips\nof getting the most out of Claude Code\nthat was just revealed by Boris, the\nhead of Claude Code. I hope this was\nhelpful. If this was, leave a like down\nbelow, subscribe, turn on notifications.\nI also live stream Monday, Wednesday,\nFriday, 11:00 a.m. Pacific. So, I'll see\nyou there. I will see you in the next\n\n2.9s · 13m 3s YouTube · 2.7k words · text via transcript/captionTracks"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":3715,"aggregated":"Transcript:\nThe creator of Claude Code just revealed\nseven secrets to get the most out of\nClaude Code and Opus 47. In this video,\nwe'll not only go over every single\nsecret he revealed, but also demonstrate\nthem live as we build an app together.\nBy the end of this video, if you follow\nalong, you'll not only be a master of\nClaude code and Opus 47, but you'll also\nhave an entire amazing app that you'll\nbuild out side by side with me, even if\nyou've never coded before a day in your\nlife. Let's lock in and get into it. So,\nBoris Churnney, one of the creators of\nClaude Code, just put out two things.\nThis amazing thread on X that goes over\nall these tips and tricks, as well as an\nentire blog post with a bunch of tips\nand tricks. What we're going to do is\nnot spend the next 20 minutes reading\nthe blog post and thread word by word\nlike every other AI channel out there.\nWe're instead going to be about that\naction boss. We're going to go in and\nimplement every sing