nwell. All right, looks like it finished\ngoing. Now, here is some really cool\nstrength of the Codex app with ChatGPT\n5.5. The integrations with so many\ndifferent tools are incredible. So,\nfirst of all, built-in browser. So, you\npop it open and you can immediately see\nit works with this built-in browser. And\nif I even go into full screen mode, you\ncan see a lot more of it. And it\nbasically looks exactly like the image\ngen we got as we were planning this,\nwhich is amazing. But let's look at some\nof the built-in tools here that there's\nbasically no other app on planet Earth\nhas. We can now start editing this app\nstraight from this live browser in\nCodex. So, there's many tools we have\nhere. First of all, we have this\nannotate. So, if I go in here, as you\ncan see as I hover around the app, it\nselects different elements and I can say\nfor it to change different things. So,\nif I want to go in here, let's add a\nfavorites button up here. So, as I'm\nbuilding a new prompt, I can immediately\nput into favorites. So, I put it there\nand I can say, \"Let's add a favorites\nbutton.\" This is one of my favorite ways\nto use ChatGPT 5.5 in Codex is instead\nof just prompting back and forth, I just\ngo straight into the app and I start\nannotating live on the app. It's like\nI'm actually building the app inside the\napp rather than just talking to a\nchatbot. So, I'm going to say this, I'm\ngoing to hit that, I'm going to add it,\nand then I'm going to hit send on that.\nAnd now it's going to get to work. This\nis one of the most fun ways for me to be\nbuilding out my apps. And boom, just\nlike that, there's your favorites\nbutton. It added. I'm not even sending\nprompts. I'm just checking off different\nthings inside the interface. So, that is\nreally, really cool. And now I can go\nback in here and continue editing\nthrough annotations if I want. But let's\ndo this. Let's say we like where the app\nis. Say we want to do testing. There's a\nlot of things here, right? There's a lot\nof things on our screen. We want to get\nit tested, but maybe we got other things\ngoing on. Maybe we're about to eat\nlunch, and when we come back, we want it\nfully tested. So, let's do this. We can\ntake advantage of computer use. This is\nagain something Claude Code does not\nhave. One of the big advantages here is\nCodex can actually use and control your\ncomputer. So, let's do this. Can you use\ncomputer use\nto test all the features of the app? And\nI'm going to hit enter on that. And what\nit's going to do now is use computer to\nactually test the app itself. Instead of\nhaving me go in and test everything,\nclick on everything, it's going to test\nitself. And look at this. So, it just\npopped open the browser with the app in\nit. And what you can see is the mouse\nthere. That's not me doing this. No\nhands, baby. It's going in, it's testing\nthe entire application itself. So, it's\ngoing through every single feature,\ntyping in things, saving, favoriting,\ndoing whatever it needs. You can even\nsee the status in the bottom left here.\nThis mouse is the computer use mouse\nthere. You can see the bottom left what\nit's thinking, what it's doing. I'm\ngoing to move this so you can see it a\nlittle bit better here. And you can see\nit go around trying the app out. So,\nthis is great for multitasking, right?\nIf you are going you're either going to\neat something or maybe you're building\nother things out. Maybe you're working\non the back end. Maybe you're doing some\nbrainstorming with the ChatGPT app. You\ncan just say, \"Hey, go in here and test\nit out. I'm going to go do something\nelse.\" This is truly like having your\nown AI employee. Look at it click around\nand do things. It really is amazing.\nThere's nothing like this in Claude Code\nat all at the moment. And it works\nreally good, too. Like you can see it's\nworking very fast. And as you saw, I was\nmoving around the window and it knew\nwhere to go, knew where to move its\nmouse, even though it was moving around\nthe window. So, this is something I\nhighly recommend doing. Have it when\nit's done building major functionality,\nsay, \"Hey, use computer use, test it out\nyourself.\" And then you can go and you\ncan multitask and try different things\nout. This is how you increase your\nefficiency a ton using Codex. So, so far\nyou can see many of the big strengths of\nChatGPT 5.5 Codex from the application\nlayer, which is the built-in browser,\nthe computer use, which is amazing, the\nannotation, the different ways to\ninteract with it and edit whatever you\nwant, the multitasking for building out\nmultiple projects. If we want to go in\nhere, start a new session, and have two\nagents building it out the same time, we\ncan do that. And then just on top of\nthat, the model itself is so much\nsmarter. And you have the integrations\nwith the image gen model, which again, I\nthink is an absolute game-changer. The\nby far the best image gen model on\nplanet Earth. But let me show you a\nlittle bit of a more advanced workflow\nhere. We went over a lot of the\nstrengths. Let's talk about how to take\nthis up the next notch. Here is a free\napp you need to be using with Codex that\nfits together like peanut butter and\njelly. This is a completely free app. It\nis called Linear, and it super powers\nCodex to a whole new level. It's\ncompletely free. The free tier is very,\nvery nice for this. You can basically\nuse this without paying at all. And it\nbasically acts as a project management\ntool for Codex. Codex is fully\nintegrated with this, and Codex can\ncompletely control this. So, as you are\nbuilding out projects, it can create\ntasks, which in Linear is called issues,\nfill up the task board, and then keep\ntrack everything it wants to build. It\nkind of acts as a second brain for\nCodex. And when I combine Linear with\nCodex, it made Codex so much smarter and\neasier to use. So, here is your advanced\nworkflow. What you want to do is first\ninstall Linear. I'm not sponsored by\nthem. This is just an amazing tool to\nuse in combo with Codex. Create a new\nteam for whatever app you're building at\nthe moment. So, I have a team for Henry\nIntelligent Machines, which is my new\nstartup, Creator Buddy, which is my old\nstartup. And what we're going to do is\nthis. If you haven't connected the two\nyet, just go in and say, \"Hey, I have\nLinear on my computer. Can you connect\nwith it?\" And it will figure out how to\nconnect with it very easily for you.\nOnce you have it connected, which again,\njust send that prompt, you'll be good to\ngo. Now we can start using it as a\nsecond brain. So, here's what we're\ngoing to do. Watch this. So, I'm going\nto say, \"Hey, can you go into the\nCreator Buddy team and build a new\nproject for this prompt library app?\"\nSo, it's going to basically go into my\nCreator Buddy workspace. I don't feel\nlike making a new one for this video.\nSo, we're going to use it as an example.\nCreate a new project for this app we're\nbuilding here. And then add issues for\nfuture features and changes we want to\nmake. Issues again is just tasks. I'm\ngoing to hit enter on that. And it is\nnow going to go in and start building\nout the project and all the tasks. And\nnow as we work, it's actually going to\nmove the tasks along the task board and\nmanage itself. So, it came up with a\nwhole bunch of new tasks it can make.\nI'm going to say, \"Yes, that looks\ngood.\" And what we're going to see here\nis as I pull open Linear and I go into\nprojects, and there's the prompt library\napp. It's building as we speak. I'm not\nadding any of this myself. And I'm going\nto go in, I'm going to look at issues.\nAnd you can see as I'm talking, new\nissues are being put in by Codex. I'm\nnot even touching this at all. It's just\ngoing in. And now if I go over to the\nissues tab, I can say all issues, and we\ncan see everything. So, we can see what\nproject it's in, we can see the\ncategories it's