 So, as these are building,\nwe have the two agents going and\nbuilding out our project for us. What\nI'm always doing is I'm going in, and\nI'm going, \"Based on the project we are\nworking on, what are some marketing\nstrategies we can implement?\" And I'm\njust brainstorming marketing, product,\nwhat should we work on next, how can we\nimprove this, what will customers think\nof this, constantly brainstorming and\nmaking sure we're multitasking. Instead\nof sitting there and doom scrolling\nTikTok, right, melting our brain out of\nour ears, we're instead going back and\nforth. We're looking for this little\nblue dot here, which means our agent is\ndone, and then we're going on there and\ncontinuing work. This is how you get\nmaximum productivity, and this is all\nunlocked because Codex is really, really\namazing. Now, let's talk about Opus 47\nand Claude Code, the big elephant in the\nroom. Everyone who's watched this\nchannel before knows I'm a Claude Code\nguy. I've been a Claude Code guy since\nday one, since it released in March. I\nstopped using basically every other tool\nonce it came out because I was just so\nblown away. And for the last basically\nyear in change, it has not been\ndethroned. It's been the champion. It's\nbeen the Tom Brady of coding. Does what\nI just show you, does what I just showed\nyou dethrone the goat, dethrone the\nking? Well, let's talk about strengths\nand weaknesses. So, first of all, when\nit comes to app, the Claude Code desktop\napp in Codex, literally 3 days ago, I\nmade a video saying Claude Code desktop\napp was the best way to divide code, and\nthen Codex comes out with a monster mega\napp update, and it beats it. It just\nbeats it. So, 3 days later, I'm saying\nCodex is better. They The update they\njust put out is amazing. Now, on the\nweakness side, there is no Codex mobile\napp, but I'm hearing from a little\nbirdie, chirp, chirp, chirp in my ear,\nthe Codex mobile app is coming very,\nvery soon. So, better app, we're going\nto go with Codex at the moment. Let's\ntalk about model. The better model is\nChatGPT 5.5. Opus 47 when it came out\nwas amazing. And much like every other\nAnthropic model, for some reason, as\ntime goes on, basically once you get\npast the first week of it being out, it\ngets significantly stupider. It is so\nfrustrating, and it is like clockwork.\nIt happens every single time. And\nsomething that frustrates me is they\ndeny it on Twitter. I don't know why.\nThis happens over and over and over\nagain. And then they deny it on Twitter\nwhen everyone and their mothers knows\nit's getting stupider. I can tell you\nwhat's happening. It's pretty obvious\nwhat's happening and why this keeps\nhappening with Claude. Anthropic simply\ndoesn't have enough compute. Something\nthey prided themselves on very early on,\nwhich I thought was very noble at the\ntime, was they didn't go out and\nmortgage their entire future on compute.\nThey didn't go out and sign $500 billion\ncontracts with Nvidia when they don't\neven have nearly that much money, which\nis something OpenAI did. They basically\nbet not only their future, but the\nentire global economy's future on\ncompute demands going up. They signed\nthese huge contracts with money they\ndidn't have. I think that safe bet from\nClaude is now biting them in the butt.\nThey simply do not have enough compute\nto keep serving Claude at these really\nintelligent levels. And there's a lot of\nevidence to support this. There's not\nonly the feel of the models getting\nworse, there's also limits going down.\nLimits keep going down. Everyone's\nexperiencing this. Everyone feels like\ntheir limits are going faster and faster\nand faster. They release new tools like\nClaude designing. You basically can use\nit twice a week before hitting your\nlimits. On top of that, they took out\nClaude Code out of the $20 plan. It's a\nlittle experiment they were running with\npeople. They started taking out of the\n$20 plan. Every decision Anthropic's\nmaking right now is pointing to the fact\nthat they just do not have enough GPUs.\nThey don't have enough compute. And so,\nbecause of this, it is very clear now\nthat 5.5 is the best model. And one\nthing that ChatGPT does is they don't\nmake the model stupider. The model feels\npretty consistently smart from the time\nthey release it to the end of life of\nit. And it shows that Sam Altman's bet\non buying outrageous amounts of compute\nwas the right bet to make cuz not only\ndoes the model not get stupider, the\nlimits are a thousand times better,\nright? So, that's another advantage, way\nhigher limits. You can use this a ton\neven on the $20 plan. That's probably\nenough limits for a vast majority of\npeople. You get way higher limits. And\nwhat's amazing [laughter]\nis, if I don't know if you're in the\nTwitterverse right now, but they reset\nthe limits basically every day. Anytime\nthey even find the smallest bug, they go\nahead. The guy's name is Tibo. He\nbasically just goes, \"Hey, limits\nreset.\" It's pretty amazing. So, you\nbasically have unlimited usage, not\nliterally, but basically have unlimited\nusage of ChatGPT, which is awesome. And\nthen, the other strength of Codex is the\nintegrations, right? So, the\nintegrations with, the biggest one being\nin my opinion, the image gen model. The\nimage gen model is amazing. I use it for\nso many things for design. I have a\ndesign video from a few days ago you\nshould check out where I talk about the\nimage gen model a ton. It really is\namazing. But that doesn't mean 5.5's\nperfect, right? No No app is perfect.\nOpus still has strengths. What are those\nstrengths? Better UI. It It just comes\ndown to it. Claude is still better at\nUI. The default UIs, if I just say build\nan app, build an app, come out way\nbetter in Claude. It hasn't improved\nwith ChatGPT. It's still not great. It\nstill feels like slop. If you do what I\nshowed you in this video, which is use\nthe image gen model to come up with user\ninterfaces, you get closer and closer\nand closer. But at the end of the day,\nClaude still has better default user\ninterfaces. I hope they improve this.\nMaybe GPT-6 will make them catch up. But\nit's still not there. When it comes to\npersonality, still better. The gap has\ncertainly closed. The gap has certainly\nclosed, but it's still not there yet.\nFrom a pure having fun chatting with the\nmodel perspective, I still have more fun\nchatting with Opus 47. It still feels\nwarmer, more friendly, and more\nimportantly, it gets to the point a lot\nfaster. It's a lot more concise, but in\na very good concise way. I still get\nfrustrated sometimes with ChatGPT 5.5\nwhere I feel like I'm reading a novel.\nEvery time I I say, \"Change the color of\nthe button,\" it comes back with a\n10-page novel on how to change the color\nof the button. I don't need all of that.\nOpus still has a better personality, but\nagain, that shrunk. Also, from a\npersonality perspective, this now margin\nis razor thin here, but it also is\nslightly better at taking action, being\na little bit more proactive. The\nmetaphor I use all the time is, if\nChatGPT and Claude are running a\nmarathon together, if you cut off\nClaude's leg halfway through the\nmarathon, it will crawl the rest of the\nway of the race. If ChatGPT stubs its\ntoe, it'll just roll over and give up.\nThat is now, I'd say, a much thinner\nmargin where ChatGPT is a lot better at\ntaking action, but Claude still has that\nkind of can-do-it attitude where it just\nfigures out a way. So, which is better?\nHas ChatGPT 5.5,\nafter over a year of Claude being the\nking when it comes to the ideal coding\nexperience, did ChatGPT\ndethrone them? Is it over? Which is the\nwinner? Have I fully switched over my\nworkflow? Well, do I have news for you?\nThe new winner is ChatGPT 5.5 Codex.\nBetween the quality of the application\nexperience and the quality of the model,\nI have switched over to 5.5 Codex. It is\nbetter. It is better for coding. Between\nthe higher limits, the model not getting\nstupider, the integrations, the\nexperience,\nI don't see any reason to be using\nClaude Code at the moment. I will say\nthis, this is a reply I get all the\ntime. I don't really get it. I am not\nloyal to any company. If Claude Code\ndrops Opus 5 tomorrow, and it is a\nbetter experience than 5.5, I will fully\nswitch over again. I get this reply all\nthe time. \"Well, last week you said\nClaude's better, and the week before\nthat you said ChatGPT's better.\" Well,\nyeah, no kidding. They're both improving\nat rapid paces. So, right now, at the\ntiming of this video, for the first time\nin over a year, ChatGPT 5.5 is the\nbetter way to be building applications\nand using AI. If things change, I'll let\nyou know. Make sure you subscribe and\nturn on notifications. I also livestream\nMonday, Wednesday, Friday 11:00 a.m.\nPacific. So, you'll see me use these\ntools live, but I'll let you know if\nthere is some sort of change here. But\nat the moment, the impossible has\nhappened. After a year and a half of\nbeing the undisputed champion, ChatGPT\n5.5's on top. Now, this is a different\nstory when it comes to open claw. I will\ndo a follow-up video on open claw. Which\nshould you be using? Claude or ChatGPT?\nMake sure to turn on notifications for\nthat. That's coming very, very soon. And\nagain, live boot camp on Codex in the\nVibe Coding Academy. Join over 1,500\npeople who joined and loved the\nexperience. Link for that is down below.\nI hope you learned something in this\nvideo. I'm so grateful you take the time\nto watch my video, see how I work, and\nlearn something from it. It really means\nthe world that you'd watch these videos.\nSo, thank you. Thank you. Thank you. I'm\nnot paid by any of these companies. I\ntruly try to be as unbiased as humanly\npossible, and I hope you can detect that\nin the way I go through these tools.\nThank you so much for watching, and I'll\nsee you in the next video.\n