he big comparison with this in Claude Code with the final recommendation. So, stick around for that. By the way, if you learned anything at all so far, make sure to leave a like down below. Subscribe, turn notifications. Coming up in the next week, I'll do a live boot camp of Codex inside the Vibe Coding Academy. The link for that is down below. It's the number one AI community on planet Earth, so check that out as well. All right, looks like it finished going. Now, here is some really cool strength of the Codex app with ChatGPT 5.5. The integrations with so many different tools are incredible. So, first of all, built-in browser. So, you pop it open and you can immediately see it works with this built-in browser. And if I even go into full screen mode, you can see a lot more of it. And it basically looks exactly like the image gen we got as we were planning this, which is amazing. But let's look at some of the built-in tools here that there's basically no other app on planet Earth has. We can now start editing this app straight from this live browser in Codex. So, there's many tools we have here. First of all, we have this annotate. So, if I go in here, as you can see as I hover around the app, it selects different elements and I can say for it to change different things. So, if I want to go in here, let's add a favorites button up here. So, as I'm building a new prompt, I can immediately put into favorites. So, I put it there and I can say, \"Let's add a favorites button.\" This is one of my favorite ways to use ChatGPT 5.5 in Codex is instead of just prompting back and forth, I just go straight into the app and I start annotating live on the app. It's like I'm actually building the app inside the app rather than just talking to a chatbot. So, I'm going to say this, I'm going to hit that, I'm going to add it, and then I'm going to hit send on that. And now it's going to get to work. This is one of the most fun ways for me to be building out my apps. And boom, just like that, there's your favorites button. It added. I'm not even sending prompts. I'm just checking off different things inside the interface. So, that is really, really cool. And now I can go back in here and continue editing through annotations if I want. But let's do this. Let's say we like where the app is. Say we want to do testing. There's a lot of things here, right? There's a lot of things on our screen. We want to get it tested, but maybe we got other things going on. Maybe we're about to eat lunch, and when we come back, we want it fully tested. So, let's do this. We can take advantage of computer use. This is again something Claude Code does not have. One of the big advantages here is Codex can actually use and control your computer. So, let's do this. Can you use computer use to test all the features of the app? And I'm going to hit enter on that. And what it's going to do now is use computer to actually test the app itself. Instead of having me go in and test everything, click on everything, it's going to test itself. And look at this. So, it just popped open the browser with the app in it. And what you can see is the mouse there. That's not me doing this. No hands, baby. It's going in, it's testing the entire application itself. So, it's going through every single feature, typing in things, saving, favoriting, doing whatever it needs. You can even see the status in the bottom left here. This mouse is the computer use mouse there. You can see the bottom left what it's thinking, what it's doing. I'm going to move this so you can see it a little bit better here. And you can see it go around trying the app out. So, this is great for multitasking, right? If you are going you're either going to eat something or maybe you're building other things out. Maybe you're working on the back end. Maybe you're doing some brainstorming with the ChatGPT app. You can just say, \"Hey, go in here and test it out. I'm going to go do something else.\" This is truly like having your own AI employee. Look at it click around and do things. It really is amazing. There's nothing like this in Claude Code at all at the moment. And it works really good, too. Like you can see it's working very fast. And as you saw, I was moving around the window and it knew where to go, knew where to move its mouse, even though it was moving around the window. So, this is something I highly recommend doing. Have it when it's done building major functionality, say, \"Hey, use computer use, test it out yourself.\" And then you can go and you can multitask and try different things out. This is how you increase your efficiency a ton using Codex. So, so far you can see many of the big strengths of ChatGPT 5.5 Codex from the application layer, which is the built-in browser, the computer use, which is amazing, the annotation, the different ways to interact with it and edit whatever you want, the multitasking for building out multiple projects. If we want to go in here, start a new session, and have two agents building it out the same time, we can do that. And then just on top of that, the model itself is so much smarter. And you have the integrations with the image gen model, which again, I think is an absolute game-changer. The by far the best image gen model on planet Earth. But let me show you a little bit of a more advanced workflow here. We went over a lot of the strengths. Let's talk about how to take this up the next notch. Here is a free app you need to be using with Codex that fits together like peanut butter and jelly. This is a completely free app. It is called Linear, and it super powers Codex to a whole new level. It's completely free. The free tier is very, very nice for this. You can basically use this without paying at all. And it basically acts as a project management tool for Codex. Codex is fully integrated with this, and Codex can completely control this. So, as you are building out projects, it can create tasks, which in Linear is called issues, fill up the task board, and then keep track everything it wants to build. It kind of acts as a second brain for Codex. And when I combine Linear with Codex, it made Codex so much smarter and easier to use. So, here is your advanced workflow. What you want to do is first install Linear. I'm not sponsored by them. This is just an amazing tool to use in combo with Codex. Create a new team for whatever app you're building at the moment. So, I have a team for Henry Intelligent Machines, which is my new startup, Creator Buddy, which is my old startup. And what we're going to do is this. If you haven't connected the two yet, just go in and say, \"Hey, I have Linear on my computer. Can you connect with it?\" And it will figure out how to connect with it very easily for you. Once you have it connected, which again, just send that prompt, you'll be good to go. Now we can start using it as a second brain. So, here's what we're going to do. Watch this. So, I'm going to say, \"Hey, can you go into the Creator Buddy team and build a new project for this prompt library app?\" So, it's going to basically go into my Creator Buddy workspace. I don't feel like making a new one for this video. So, we're going to use it as an example. Create a new project for this app we're building here. Then add issues for future features and changes we want to make. Issues again is just tasks. I'm going to hit enter on that. And it is now going to go in and start building out the project and all the tasks. And now as we work, it's actually going to move the tasks along the task board and manage itself. So, it came up with a whole bunch of new tasks it can make. I'm going to say, \"Yes, that looks good.\" And what we're going to see here is as I pull open Linear and I go into projects, and there's the prompt library app. It's building as we speak. I'm not adding any of this myself. And I'm going to go in, I'm going to look at issues. And you can see as I'm talking, new issues are being put in by Codex. I'm not even touching this at all. It's just going in. And now if I go over to the issues tab, I can say all issues, and we can see everything. So, we can see what project it's in, we can see the categories it's giving it. If I double-click and go in, it actually adds details to the issues. Before Codex, this was hours and hours and hours of work to manage these tasks. Now with Codex, it's going in in just a few seconds, it created like 10 issues, gave it full details, full categories, everything like that. And now it can manage itself and keep organized on everything we want to build. And the best part is this unlocks great multitasking inside of Codex. So, if I go in and I start a new session inside of our project here, I can say, \"Hey, do you see the tasks in Linear for this project inside Creator Buddy?\" And I hit enter, and it's going to be able to see those tasks. And I can say, \"Hey, start working on those tasks.\" And now we have these two agents working side by side off the same data set, right? Off the same project management tool, and working together. It allows the agents to collaborate by using that same second brain together. This unlocks so much power cuz now you can work 10 times faster. I can load up, have five different agents going, and just working across our linear issues. What you were doing before is you were loading up new agents, and you had to remind them every single time, \"Look through the codebase. Here's everything we're working on. Here's what's next.\" That all that work is now eliminated because of Linear being integrated. Again, I'm not sponsored by any of these people. No one's paying me. ChatGPT ain't paying me. Linear ain't paying me. I just love using these tools, and this is the best workflow I've ever created. I go into my official recommendation and compare this with Opus 47 and Claude Code, make sure you do this. Get the Codex app downloaded, download Linear, and start using them side by side because all your projects are going to start going much faster. And then, one last tip I'll give you before we do the comparison, use chats. So, again, chats are fully built into Codex. So, as these are building, we have the two agents going and building out our project for us. What I'm always doing is I'm going in, and I'm going, \"Based on the project we are working on, what are some marketing strategies we can implement?\" And I'm just brainstorming marketing, product, what should we work on next, how can we improve this, what will customers think of this, constantly brainstorming and making sure we're multitasking. Instead of sitting there and doom scrolling TikTok, right, melting our brain out of our ears, we're instead going back and forth. We're looking for this little blue dot here, which means our agent is done, and then we're going on there and continuing work. This is how you get maximum productivity, and this is all unlocked because Codex is really, really amazing. Now, let's talk about Opus 47 and Claude Code, the big elephant in the room. Everyone who's watched this channel before knows I'm a Claude Code guy. I've been a Claude Code guy since day one, since it released in March. I stopped using basically every other tool once it came out because I was just so blown away. And for the last basically year in change, it has not been dethroned. It's been the champion. It's been the Tom Brady of coding. Does what I just show you, does what I just showed you dethrone the goat, dethrone the king? Well, let's talk about strengths and weaknesses. So, first of all, when it comes to app, the Claude Code desktop app in Codex, literally 3 days ago, I made a video saying Claude Code desktop app was the best way to divide code, and then Codex comes out with a monster mega app update, and it beats it. It just beats it. So, 3 days later, I'm saying Codex is better. They The update they just put out is amazing. Now, on the weakness side, there is no Codex mobile app, but I'm hearing from a little birdie, chirp, chirp, chirp in my ear, the Codex mobile app is coming very, very soon. So, better app, we're going to go with Codex at the moment. Let's talk about model. The better model is ChatGPT 5.5. Opus 47 when it came out was amazing. And much like every other Anthropic model, for some reason, as time goes on, basically once you get past the first week of it being out, it gets significantly stupider. It is so frustrating, and it is like clockwork. It happens every single time. And something that frustrates me is they deny it on Twitter. I don't know why. This happens over and over and over again. And then they deny it on Twitter when everyone and their mothers knows it's getting stupider. I can tell you what's happening. It's pretty obvious what's happening and why this keeps happening with Claude. Anthropic simply doesn't have enough compute. Something they prided themselves on very early on, which I thought was very noble at the time, was they didn't go out and mortgage their entire future on compute. They didn't go out and sign $500 billion contracts with Nvidia when they don't even have nearly that much money, which is something OpenAI did. They basically bet not only their future, but the entire global economy's future on compute demands going up. They signed these huge contracts with money they didn't have. I think that safe bet from Claude is now biting them in the butt. They simply do not have enough compute to keep serving Claude at these really intelligent levels. And there's a lot of evidence to support this. There's not only the feel of the models getting worse, there's also limits going down. Limits keep going down. Everyone's experiencing this. Everyone feels like their limits are going faster and faster and faster. They release new tools like Claude designing. You basically can use it twice a week before hitting your limits. On top of that, they took out Claude Code out of the $20 plan. It's a little experiment they were running with people. They started taking out of the $20 plan. Every decision Anthropic's making right now is pointing to the fact that they just do not have enough GPUs. They don't have enough compute. And so, because of this, it is very clear now that 5.5 is the best model. And one thing that ChatGPT does is they don't make the model stupider. The model feels pretty consistently smart from the time they release it to the end of life of it. And it shows that Sam Altman's bet on buying outrageous amounts of compute was the right bet to make cuz not only does the model not get stupider, the limits are a thousand times better, right? So, that's another advantage, way higher limits. You can use this a ton even on the $20 plan. That's probably enough limits for a vast majority of people. You get way higher limits. And what's amazing is, if I don't know if you're in the Twitterverse right now, but they reset the limits basically every day. Anytime they even find the smallest bug, they go ahead. The guy's name is Tibo. He basically just goes, \"Hey, limits reset.\" It's pretty amazing. So, you basically have unlimited usage, not literally, but basically have unlimited usage of ChatGPT, which is awesome. And then, the other strength of Codex is the integrations, right? So, the integrations with, the biggest one being in my opinion, the image gen model. The image gen model is amazing. I use it for so many things for design. I have a design video from a few days ago you should check out where I talk about the image gen model a ton. It really is amazing. But that doesn't mean 5.5's perfect, right? No No app is perfect. Opus still has strengths. What are those strengths? Better UI. It just comes down to it. Claude is still better at UI. The default UIs, if I just say build an app, build an app, come out way better in Claude. It hasn't improved with ChatGPT. It's still not great. It still feels like slop. If you do what I showed you in this video, which is use the image gen model to come up with user interfaces, you get closer and closer and closer. But at the end of the day, Claude still has better default user interfaces. I hope they improve this. Maybe GPT-6 will make them catch up. But it's still not there. When it comes to personality, still better. The gap has certainly closed. The gap has certainly closed, but it's still not there yet. From a pure having fun chatting with the model perspective, I still have more fun chatting with Opus 47. It still feels warmer, more friendly, and more importantly, it gets to the point a lot faster. It's a lot more concise, but in a very good concise way. I still get frustrated sometimes with ChatGPT 5.5 where I feel like I'm reading a novel. Every time I say, \"Change the color of the button,\" it comes back with a 10-page novel on how to change the color of the button. I don't need all of that. Opus still has a better personality, but again, that shrunk. Also, from a personality perspective, this now margin is razor thin here, but it also is slightly better at taking action, being a little bit more proactive. The metaphor I use all the time is, if ChatGPT and Claude are running a marathon together, if you cut off Claude's leg halfway through the marathon, it will crawl the rest of the way of the race. If ChatGPT stubs its toe, it'll just roll over and give up. That is now, I'd say, a much thinner margin where ChatGPT is a lot better at taking action, but Claude still has that kind of can-do-it attitude where it just figures out a way. So, which is better? Has ChatGPT 5.5, after over a year of Claude being the king when it comes to the ideal coding experience, did ChatGPT dethrone them? Is it over? Which is the winner? Have I fully switched over my workflow? Well, do I have news for you? The new winner is ChatGPT 5.5 Codex. Between the quality of the application experience and the quality of the model, I have switched over to 5.5 Codex. It is better. It is better for coding. Between the higher limits, the model not getting stupider, the integrations, the experience, I don't see any reason to be using Claude Code at the moment. I will say this, this is a reply I get all the time. I don't really get it. I am not loyal to any company. If Claude Code drops Opus 5 tomorrow, and it is a better experience than 5.5, I will fully switch over again. I get this reply all the time. \"Well, last week you said Claude's better, and the week before that you said ChatGPT's better.\" Well, yeah, no kidding. They're both improving at rapid paces. So, right now, at the timing of this video, for the first time in over a year, ChatGPT 5.5 is the better way to be building applications and using AI. If things change, I'll let you know. Make sure you subscribe and turn on notifications. I also livestream Monday, Wednesday, Friday 11:00 a.m. Pacific. So, you'll see me use these tools live, but I'll let you know if there is some sort of change here. But at the moment, the impossible has happened. After a year and a half of being the undisputed champion, ChatGPT 5.5's on top. Now, this is a different story when it comes to open claw. I will do a follow-up video on open claw. Which should you be using? Claude or ChatGPT? Make sure to turn on notifications for that. That's coming very, very soon. And again, live boot camp on Codex in the Vibe Coding Academy. Join over 1,500 people who joined and loved the experience. Link for that is down below. I hope you learned something in this video. I'm so grateful you take the time to watch my video, see how I work, and learn something from it. It really means the world that you'd watch these videos. So, thank you. Thank you. Thank you. I'm not paid by any of these companies. I truly try to be as unbiased as humanly possible, and I hope you can detect that in the way I go through these tools. Thank you so much for watching, and I'll see you in the next video.\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":15688,"output