{"type":"message","id":"bc99fad0","parentId":"fcbc4f3e","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:42:24.489Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_dxzhia4kpd0u_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nOpenClaw is the most powerful AI tool\never made. And after using it nonstop\nfor the last 3 months, I can confidently\nsay no one else on planet Earth has used\nit as much as I have. I've used it to\ngrow my businesses, to build brand new\nbusinesses that just raised funding.\nI've exploded my revenue with it. I've\nexploded all my social channels with it\nand created tons and tons of content.\nI've used it to improve basically every\naspect of my business and personal life.\nIn this video, I'll go over every single\nopen claw lesson I've learned over that\ntime period. Whether you are brand new\nto openclaw or a stone cold expert, I\npromise you are going to learn something\namazing in this video. So, now let's\nlock in and get into it. So, before we\njump in, feel free to check out the\nchapters down below. If you've used Open\nClaw in the past or if you've watched\npast videos I've made, I'm probably\ngoing to cover some things that you're\nalready familiar with. So, feel free to\ngo down below, check out different\nchapters, jump around. I want to make\nsure I cover new things for you here.\nBut, let's start off with why OpenClaw\nis the goat and what it is. Open Claw is\na completely autonomous AI agent. It is\nbasically your own personal AI employee\nthat works for you 24/7 and does\nwhatever you need. I'll show you what my\nOpen Claw does in this video, but it is\na completely autonomous employee that's\nbuilding things for me 247, researching\nthings for me, scraping things off the\nweb, getting actions done, posting\ncontent, all of that. It's\nself-improving. Every time I send it a\nmessage, it improves, builds skills,\nfigures out new ways to do things. It is\ntenacious and incredible. It does\nwhatever a human can do. So, it manages\nall my devices for me. It builds apps\nfor me. It changes settings for me. If\nyou notice down below all the members of\nthe Finn family, I just said, \"Hey,\nbuild me new logos and put it on YouTube\nfor me. It designs new logos, then went\non YouTube Studio and uploaded them for\nme.\" It literally does whatever a human\ncan do. And here's the best part. Here's\nwhere it really differentiates itself\nfrom the claw codes, clawed co-works,\ncodeexes of the world. It is completely\nopen source, meaning your data stays on\nyour device. It doesn't go to the\nservers of AI labs or anything like\nthat. And you can see how the data\nflows, what it does, and it is\ncompletely customizable. If you want to\ndownload the source code of openclaw and\nchange it and fork it and do whatever\nyou want with the code, you can do that.\nIt's completely open source and up to\nyou. If you want to plug in different\nmodels, you can do that. Claude code,\nclaw co-work, you can only use clawed\nmodels. Codeex, you can only use Chad\nGPT models. With open clause, since it's\nopen source, you can use whatever models\nyou want. If you want to use local\nmodels that run on your device\ncompletely for free, you can do that,\ntoo. And I'll cover all of that later in\nthe video. We're covering everything,\nuse cases, models, devices, all of that,\nall the lessons. This is going to be\ncomprehensive. It's also private and\nsecure. So, all your data stays on your\ndevice and they have made huge\nimprovements when it comes to security.\nI will also cover security on this video\nas well. Here's my favorite part about\nOpenClaw is it lives where you work. I\nhave it in Telegram. I have a bunch of\nopen claws and Hermes agents and other\nagents here on the left. Every one of\nthese you see that has a letter on it is\na different open claw or Hermes agent. I\nalso cover openclaw versus Hermes later\nas well cuz that's a big controversy\nright now on Twitter, but it lives where\nI live. I can go on Telegram anywhere in\nthe world on my devices on my phone.\nSay, \"Hey, do this for me.\" And it'll go\non my computer and build a whole bunch\nof things out. You don't have to have 20\ndifferent apps to use it. Just all goes\nin your Telegram and it works really,\nreally well. Now, let's talk about where\nto host your Open Claw. What device it\nneeds to be on. Doesn't need to be on a\nMac Mini like this, or can it just be on\nanything? Let me just start off by\nsaying this. Host it literally anywhere\nexcept for a VPS. I know if you go on to\nliterally any other AI YouTube channel\nright now, basically every video is\nsponsored by Hostinger. I will tell you\nthis, none of the creators that are\nsponsored by Hostinger are actually\nputting their open claw on Hostinger. Do\nnot put your open claws on VPS's. They\nare a considerably worse experience.\nThey are less secure. They are less\nusable. They are less powerful. There\nare zero zero zero advantages to putting\nyour OpenClaw on a VPS. You need to have\nthis on a local device. I will never\ntake a sponsorship from any of these VPS\ncompanies. I can't in my good conscience\ntell you to put your open claw on a VPS\nwhen I am not personally doing it\nmyself. But does that mean you need to\nrun out and buy a $600 Mac Mini? No,\nthat doesn't. You can put this on\nliterally anything. This is like the\nmost misqued thing I say. Everyone goes,\n\"Oh, Alex Finn's the Mac Mini guy.\"\nYou're right. I do like it on Mac Minis,\nbut you do not need to buy a Mac Mini\nfor this. You can go take that old\nLenovo computer with the red little nub\nin the middle of it in the keyboard that\nyou were using 15 years ago in college.\nTake that out of your closet, plug it in\nfor the first time and put open claw on\nthat. You do not need to buy a new\ndevice for this. You will still get\nincredible power out of this. But here's\nthe thing. If you do want to upgrade and\nyou do want to put it on a Mac Mini,\nit's going to be an amazing experience\nfor many different reasons. Mac Mini is\none of the most usable, best values in\ncomputing I think on planet Earth. I\nlove having it on my desk knowing\nthere's an AI agent working on it 247.\nIt's fun to play with. It's fun to\ncustomize. You can easily remote into it\nfrom any other computer you have. Mac\nminis are great values and great\ndevices. That's why a lot of people are\ngoing on buying them for these agents\nbecause it's just the easiest way to\nhave a little device on your desk\nknowing an agent's working 24/7. You can\nput OpenClaw on your main driver\ncomputer, the one you use every day.\nThat's totally fine. I do it myself, but\nI also have other devices that I'm\nputting on as well. So, it has its own\nworkspace, its own hard drive, its own\nfiles to use, its own tools to use. You\ndo get advantages from giving it its own\ncomputer, but you don't need to do that.\nNow, if you want to take it up to the\nnext level like I do, I currently have\nthree Mac Studios, two Mac Minis, and a\nDJX Spark. You don't need to do what I'm\ndoing. Don't run down and just buy all\nthose cuz I'm doing it. But there are\nadvantages to doing that as well. You\nget to run the most frontier local\nmodels, which basically are, and I'll go\ninto deeper detail on this a little bit\nlater, models that run on your devices\nthat don't connect to the internet, that\nare fully private and secure. It allows\nyou to unlock a lot more use cases. So,\nit is more power. The more computers you\nhave, the more powerful computers have,\nthe more power you get. But as long as\nyou just install this on, I'm serious,\nany device you have, any device at all,\nyou're going to be so far ahead of\neveryone else in the world because\nyou're going to be using the most\npowerful AI technology locally in your\noffice on your desk and it's going to be\namazing. One last recommendation before\nwe move on to which models to be using.\nI would scale into this slowly. A lot of\npeople that watch this go and spend\n$20,000 on Mac Studios after watching my\nvideos. And listen, that's amazing. I'm\nproud of you. I think you're making a\ngood decision. But I think for a vast\nmajority of people out there, it's much\nsmarter to start small and then scale\nup. Start small, put it on the dusty\nlaptop from your closet, start to get\nsome use out of it, and then once you're\ncomfortable with the workflows, then you\ncan buy a Mac Mini. And then once you've\nutilized all the hardware inside the Mac\nMini and you're ready to start hosting\nlocal models, then you can buy a Mac\nStudio. And then once you've done that,\nyou've maxed out the Mac Studio, then go\nbuy another one, right? Start small,\nscale up. I think that's a probably a\nlot smarter for most people than just\ngoing out and dropping tens of thousands\nof dollars on computers. So, let's talk\nabout models. This is a big one. This is\nwhere there's tons of controversy. I'm\ngoing to give it to you straight. I've\nbeen using OpenClaw for hundreds of\nhours now. I am extremely confident\nabout in the recommendations I'm about\nto give you here. Orchestrator. This is\nthe brain of your agent. This is what\ndecides which task to do and how to do\nit. You need to be using Opus 47. Now, I\nknow what you're going to say. But\ndidn't they ban Opus? Didn't they ban\nAnthropic? Yes, Anthropic banned the use\nof OpenClaw inside of its subscriptions,\nright? So, you can't pay for the $20,\nthe $200 subscription and use those\nsubsidized tokens with OpenClaw, but you\ncan still use it with the API. Now, yes,\nit's going to be expensive using it with\nthe API. If you optimize this correctly,\nit's not going to be that much more\nexpensive. And I'll talk about\noptimization a little bit later as well.\nIf you use this the right way, you won't\nbe paying much more than that $200 a\nmonth. But at the end of the day, here's\nwhat it comes down to. When it comes to\norchestrating of AI agents, when it\ncomes to coming up with tasks and then\ncompleting those tasks, no model comes\nremotely close to Opus 47. Not Chad GBT.\nNone of them. And I'm not getting paid\nby any of these companies. Anthropic,\nOpenAI, Google, none of them have ever\npaid me in my life. This is truly based\non my experience. I've tested them all.\nClaude is the only model where if you\ngive it a task, you can be extremely\nconfident it will complete that task. I\nlove Chad GBT. I love using Chad GBT. I\nlove to chat with it. I love to code\nwith it. But as a orchestrator for Open\nClaw or any other AI agent out there,\nHermes, it just simply is not as\nreliable based on my experiences. And I\nhope this changes. Open AAI has been\nvery very consumerfriendly when it comes\nto limits and when it comes to using\nyour subscription for whatever you want.\nAnthropic has changed limits a good\namount and they don't want you using\ntheir subscription with different tools.\nOpenAI has been more consumerfriendly.\nSo I am rooting for open AAI to improve\nchat GBT with open claw but we have to\nface the facts which is Claude just\nbeats chat GPT for openclaw usage and to\ngive you a quick example a quick\nmetaphor on why I believe this when\ngiving open claw powered by claude a\ntask you can be near 100% certain it\nwill complete that task no matter what\nyou can go up to claude with a katana\nsword and cut off its leg halfway\nthrough a race you can be confident it\nwill crawl its ass down to the finish\nline and complete that race. With Chad\nGPT, if it even stubs its toe halfway\nthrough the race, it's just going to\nroll over and give up. I just don't have\nconfidence when I give Chad GPT a task\nin OpenClaw that it's actually going to\ncomplete that task. This is as of the\ntime of filming. That's why I do one of\nthese videos every single month is to\nupdate my opinions and thoughts on which\nmodels to use cuz it's constantly\nconstantly changing. It's rumored that\nChad GBT 5.5 is going to come out this\nweek. And you know what? It might be a\nthousand times better for Open Claw than\nClaude when it comes out. And if that's\nthe case, I'll make an updated video and\nI'll switch all my open claws over to\nChad GBT. But I'm being unbiased and I'm\njust talking about at the moment, you\nneed to be using Opus. You need to be\npaying for the API. And just in case 55\ncomes out and it's better for OpenClaw,\n\n⚠️ [... middle content omitted — showing head and tail ...]\n\nreally should be making this custom for\nyour own use cases. Copying other people\nwhether it's use cases or mission\ncontrols, it doesn't do you any good.\nFirst of all, half the fun is building\nthese things out by yourself. The other\nhalf is these need to be custom for what\nyou're doing. So mission control, build\nit out. Great reverse prompting\nopportunity. Hey, OpenClaw, based on\nwhat you know about me, what tools can\nwe add to our mission control? It'll\ngive you a list of them to say, hey,\nbuild them out and you'll be good to go.\nSo, let's talk about security. This is a\nbig one. This is one I get most\nquestions on is security. And for good\nreasons, right? You have an AI agent\nliving on your computer that can do\nanything, that has access to all your\nnudes and your photos and everything\nelse you do. You need to have good\nsecurity. But here's the thing, though.\nThere is no good blanket security\nrecommendation I can give to you, right?\nIt's an AI employee that can do anything\non your computer. If I sat here and gave\nyou every security recommendation, we'd\nbe here for 15 hours plus. So, here's\nwhat you need to do. If you can master\nthis, you'll be good on security. You\nneed to use good judgment. What do I\nmean by that? Your open claw isn't going\nto do things that you don't tell it to\ndo. What I mean by that is you're not\ngoing to say, \"Hey, write me a\nPowerPoint presentation on local\nmodels.\" And then it goes and leaks all\nyour iMes Twitter. It's not going to do\nthat. That's not how it works. It only\ndoes exactly what you tell it to do. So\nthat means you need to have some\npersonal accountability and you need to\nuse good judgment. You can't say, \"Go\nand check out all my emails,\" and then\ndelete any emails you think are spam.\nBecause if you do that, you're opening\nyourself up for OpenClaw to do things\nthat you don't want it to do. You need\nto use good judgment. You need to use\nprecise languaging on what you ask it to\ndo. And you need to think about the\nrepercussions of it doing what you ask\nit to do. My question to you is this\nbecause security makes a lot of people\nreally nervous when it comes to\nOpenClaw. How many people do you know\nhas had catastrophic security events\nbecause of OpenClaw? My guess would be\nfor 99.99999%\nof you, you don't know a single person\nwho's had a catastrophic security event.\nThat doesn't mean there aren't\nvulnerabilities. That just means there's\na lot of panic over nothing here. If you\njust use good judgment, think about\nwhat's going to happen with every prompt\nyou give it. I'm very confident bad\nthings won't happen to you. So, just\nhave some personal accountability, use\ngood judgment with your prompts, think\nabout what could happen, and you'll be\ngood to go. Again, you don't say, \"Hey,\nwrite me a tweet.\" And then it goes and\nit downloads 20 viruses onto your\ncomputer. That's not how this works.\nOpen Claw does what you say. So, if you\nwant to have good security, think about\nwhat you're asking it to do and make\nsure you're only asking it to do pretty\nsafe things. Those are all my lessons\nlearned after 300 plus hours of using\nOpenClaw. The game is constantly\nchanging. AI models are constantly\nchanging. OpenClaw is constantly\nchanging. These will update as we go all\nthe time. I mean, tomorrow a new model\ncan drop that will change everything I\njust said. So, make sure you're\nsubscribed to notifications on. So, as\nthings change, as things go, you get the\nupda