e're going to talk about a multi- aent\napproach. which we'll talk about Hermes\nin a second as well. But one last thing\nI'll leave you off with is my fa one of\nmy favorite things to do with OpenClaw\nis have it build out prototypes on the\ngo. So if I'm on the go, I'm out getting\na Big Mac in McDonald's. I'm out at the\ngym getting a huge pump on, right? I\nwill have my phone on me and whenever I\nget new ideas, the most ideas I come up\nwith either at the gym or when I'm\neating a Big Mac, I'll go on Telegram\nand I'll say, \"Hey, can you build out a\nprototype for this idea for me?\" and\nI'll just spam it with ideas all day\nlong and then when I get back to my\ncomputer, OpenClaw will have built out\nall those prototypes for me and I can\nthen just go and test them very easily.\nSo using OpenClaw as a prototype builder\nwhen you're out on the go, fantastic way\nto use it as well. And real quick before\nwe talk about the multi- aent approach,\nso talking about having multiple agents,\nmultiple open claws, having Hermes set\nup as well. This is a question you get\nall the time. when to use claw code,\nwhen to use openclaw and hermes. Claude\ncode is great for building out consumer\napplications. So big consumerf facing\napplications, very complex, a lot to it.\nYou want to be using claude code because\nclaude code is built specifically for\nvibe coding. I also like to use claude\ncode just for quick tweaks, changing\nbutton colors, things like that, just\ncuz it's easier to go into and get that\nchanged. Openclaw Hermes is great for\nbeing an advisor to building those apps\nout, right? You want to have an agent\nfor building and an agent for advising.\nOpen Claw great for advising mostly\nbecause it knows the most about you. It\nhas huge memory about you and everything\nyou do. So, it's going to be really good\nat advising on those coding projects.\nAnd it's also great at managing files on\nyour computer. So, you're changing\ndifferent things on your computer c