{"type":"message","id":"5c88399c","parentId":"1bedcd19","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:45:09.410Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Video 6 done. Now Video 7 - \"Open Claw and Hermes Agent is the most powerful combo\" and Video 8 - \"OpenClaw's memory sucks\" are both done from the summary context. Let me now save Video 7 and Video 8, then move to Video 9.\n\nWait, from the summary context:\n- Video 5 ✅ \"Claude Code Secrets\" - saved\n- Video 6 ✅ \"Claude Code Desktop Deep Dive\" - saved\n- Video 7 ⏳ \"Open Claw and Hermes Agent\" - transcript was already pulled above, need to save\n- Video 8 ⏳ \"OpenClaw's memory sucks\" - transcript was already pulled above, need to save\n\n\n- Video 9 ⏳ Next in sequence - haven't pulled yet\n\nLet me save Video 7 first, then Video 8, then pull Video 9.\n","thinkingSignature":"0027ecaae3c19ba61c3a15053696a4bed6618346a07566a0cd1cdf1274a26d57"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7zub5ilth1y7_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# OpenClaw + Hermes: The Ultimate AI Agent Combo\n\n**Channel:** Alex Finn  \n**Date:** 2026-04-27  \n**Original Video:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mduLV-mWrNM  \n**Duration:** ~16 minutes  \n**Views:** 55K  \n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nAlex explains why running OpenClaw and Hermes Agent together is the most powerful AI setup, covering reliability benefits, complementary strengths, model recommendations, and 3 key workflows.\n\n### Why Multi-Agent?\n\n- **Reliability explodes:** When one breaks, the other fixes it → downtime near zero\n- **Complementary strengths:** Different harnesses, different optimizations\n- **Cost optimization:** Use expensive models only where needed, cheap models for execution\n- **No single point of failure:** If one completely breaks, the other has the context to repair it\n\n### Strengths Breakdown\n\n| | OpenClaw | Hermes Agent |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Role** | Main agent | Assistant/Monitor |\n| **Memory** | Slightly better | Slightly faster |\n| **Weight** | Heavier | Lighter, fewer tokens |\n| **Reliability** | Very stable, quick updates | Great at assisting |\n| **Model recommendation** | Opus 4.7 (API) | ChatGPT or GLMs |\n\n**Don't think tribal warfare** — use both. They're different tools for different jobs.\n\n### Model Setup\n- OpenClaw: Opus 4.7 (best for AI agents, despite cost)\n- Hermes: ChatGPT or cheaper models (GLM) since it's the assistant\n- If on $20 ChatGPT plan, hard to run both — consider cheaper model for Hermes\n\n### Key Workflows\n\n**1. Mutual Backup / Insurance**\n- Every update risks breaking something\n- With two agents, when OpenClaw breaks after an update, Hermes jumps in and fixes it\n- Downtime went from ~1 hour to seconds\n- They know each other's code inside and out\n\n**2. Supervisor-Builder Workflow**\n- OpenClaw (Opus) plans → Hermes executes → OpenClaw reviews\n- Example: Build a scanner dashboard (Next.js)\n  1. OpenClaw creates detailed plan (256 lines)\n  2. Hands plan to Hermes → builds it\n  3. OpenClaw reviews code, provides feedback\n- Save money: expensive Opus only plans and reviews, cheaper model does execution\n\n**3. Monitor System (Cron Jobs)**\n- Schedule Hermes to check on things every 2 hours\n- Monitors scanners, processes, social media, emails — whatever OpenClaw built\n- Cheaper to run frequently = can check much more often\n- Alerts you when something goes wrong\n\n**4. Shared Memory Workspace**\n- Both agents use Obsidian as centralized memory\n- Daily logs, mistakes files, working context, shared workspace\n- Dramatically improves memory across all agents\n- One agent does something → other agents can immediately access and continue that work\n\n### Practical Tips\n- Keep both Telegram windows open on second monitor at all times\n- Creates habits of actually using them\n- Works great for vibe coding — OpenClaw for tooling, Claude Code for deep consumer apps\n- Things change fast — models/harnesses evolve, check for updates regularly","path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - OpenClaw + Hermes Combo - Alex Finn.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":755,"output":935,"cacheRead":45440,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47130,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777347832882,"responseId":"063f5ffc350d681679aaafe7a7a6a6ed"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1bee1a5c","parentId":"5c88399c","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:45:09.410Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_7zub5ilth1y7_1","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 2904 bytes to /Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - OpenClaw + Hermes Combo - Alex Finn.md"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1777347863013}}
{"type":"message","id":"1ea2df4a","parentId":"1bee1a5c","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:45:09.410Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now Video 7. Let me write it up and then move on to Video 8.\n","thinkingSignature":"8f051fbcd1f76cfd7b30ef41486252e0902ffa24cdb4499de9feb37014cfc987"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_y9jzahqgpkz1_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# OpenClaw Memory System: Obsidian Integration\n\n**Channel:** Alex Finn  \n**Date:** 2026-04-27  \n**Original Video:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6V-b073qhPA  \n**Duration:** 10 minutes 58 seconds  \n**Views:** 61K  \n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nAlex reveals his 4-layer memory system that makes OpenClaw's memory \"flawless\" using Obsidian. This solves OpenClaw's compaction forgetting problem and adds memory-on-demand capability.\n\n### The 4-Layer Memory System\n\n| Layer | What | How It Works |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Layer 1** | Built-in memory | Name, important file paths — sticky note layer |\n| **Layer 2** | Rules + Soul files | agents.md (rules), soul.md (personality) |\n| **Layer 3** | Obsidian Vault *(NEW)* | On-demand memory, not injected with every prompt |\n| **Layer 4** | Session search | History of all sessions and cron jobs |\n\n**Layer 3 is the game-changer.** It's NOT injected with every prompt — instead it's queried on-demand, avoiding context overload while providing rich memory.\n\n### Problems Solved\n\n**Compaction amnesia:** Before this system, compacting would make OpenClaw forget things from 5 seconds ago. With Obsidian integration, before every compaction it checks the vault to see what it was working on — compaction becomes unnoticeable.\n\n**Memory on demand:** Small projects worked on for 5 minutes, then abandoned for weeks — now OpenClaw can find them instantly months later via daily logs.\n\n**Multi-agent shared workspace:** Agent Shared folder lets all agents (OpenClaw, Hermes) access each other's work. If Hermes scripts a YouTube video, OpenClaw can immediately see and continue that work.\n\n### What's in the Obsidian Vault\n\n- **Daily logs:** Auto-created every day, covering everything discussed at a high level\n- **Mistakes file:** Logs every time something goes wrong so agents learn and improve\n- **Working context:** Dynamic files with whatever context each agent needs\n- **Agent Shared:** Shared workspace all agents can read/write to\n- **Knowledge base:** Long-term storage of learned information\n\n### Setup (Prompt to Give Your Agent)\n\n```\nInstall Obsidian, then give your agent this prompt:\n\nCreate a four-layer memory system using Obsidian:\nLayer 1: Built-in sticky note memory\nLayer 2: agents.md and soul.md rules\nLayer 3: Obsidian vault loaded at session start — NOT injected in every prompt, queried on-demand. Location: [YOUR_OBSIDIAN_VAULT_PATH]\nLayer 4: Session search history\n\nFlow: Start every session by checking vault for relevant context. Write daily logs automatically. Log mistakes. Before compaction, check vault. On-demand memory retrieval when referenced.\n\nAlso create a shared workspace in Agent Shared folder accessible to all agents.\n```\n\n**Important:** After setup, verify memories are actually being written. If not, tell your agent to burn the rules into agents.md.\n\n### Beyond Memory: Personal Wiki\n\nOnce the system is running, ask your agent to \"build a visual interface for our memories, like a personal wiki.\" It creates a searchable visual explorer of all memories, sources, concepts, and conversations.\n\n### Resources\n- Obsidian: free app for markdown file organization\n- Vibe Coding Academy: live boot camps and deeper dives on memory systems","path":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - OpenClaw Memory System - Alex Finn.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":864,"output":802,"cacheRead":46144,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47810,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777347863014,"responseId":"063f6017f725b9fd3c663fe60aaca735"}}
